<h2 id="represent-data-honestly">Represent data honestly</h2>
<p>Charts must represent data truthfully and support informed decisions, not visual emphasis.</p>
<ul>
  <li>Do not manipulate axis scales to exaggerate differences.</li>
  <li>Start bar charts at zero unless there is a documented reason not to.</li>
  <li>Clearly label units, timeframes and scope of the data.</li>
  <li>Avoid 3D styling or visual effects that can distort perception.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Each chart should include</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Clear title</li>
  <li>Axis labels with units</li>
  <li>Legend or direct labels</li>
  <li>Source where relevant</li>
  <li>Last updated date where relevant</li>
</ul>


<h2 id="keep-only-what-matters">Keep only what matters</h2>
<p>Only include data that supports the primary message or decision. Clarity should take priority over density.</p>
<ul>
  <li>Limit the number of data series.</li>
  <li>Avoid clutter or unnecessary visual elements.</li>
  <li>Use annotations to highlight the key insight.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Dashboards</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Place key metrics first.</li>
  <li>Group related charts.</li>
  <li>Avoid horizontal scrolling for primary information.</li>
  <li>If metadata applies to all charts, include it at the container level.</li>
</ul>


<h2 id="chart-anatomy">Chart anatomy</h2>
<p>Every chart must include the core elements required for clarity and accurate interpretation.</p>

<h3>Title</h3>
<p>Provide a clear, descriptive title that states what the data represents. Include the time period and unit of measurement where relevant.</p>

<h3>Axis labels</h3>
<p>Clearly label all axes. Include units such as percentage, dollars or count, and time intervals where applicable. Avoid abbreviations that are not widely understood.</p>

<h3>Data labels</h3>
<p>Label datasets directly where possible. Direct labelling improves readability and reduces reliance on legends. For bar and column charts, including numerical labels can improve clarity and accessibility.</p>

<h3>Legend</h3>
<p>Use legends only when direct labelling is not practical. Legends must be clearly associated with the chart, not rely solely on colour, and remain readable at 200 percent zoom.</p>

<h3>Scale</h3>
<p>Use appropriate and consistent scales. Bar charts should start at zero unless there is a documented reason not to. Clearly indicate if axes are truncated.</p>

<h3>Source and metadata</h3>
<p>Include source information where relevant, such as data source, last updated date and definitions. If multiple charts share the same source, this may be placed at the container level.</p>

<h3>Spacing and alignment</h3>
<p>Maintain consistent spacing between data elements, labels and grid lines. When colours sit adjacent to each other, include sufficient negative space to maintain clarity.</p>


<h2 id="accessibility-requirements">Accessibility requirements</h2>
<p>Charts must meet WCAG 2.2 AA and AAA where possible. Users must be able to access the same information without relying on the visual chart.</p>

<h3>Contrast</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Text must meet a minimum contrast ratio of 4.5 to 1 (WCAG 1.4.3).</li>
  <li>Graphical elements such as bars, lines, data points and focus indicators must meet a minimum contrast ratio of 3 to 1 against adjacent colours and background (WCAG 1.4.11).</li>
  <li>Test contrast in the rendered environment, not just in design files.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Use of colour</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Colour must not be the only way to communicate meaning (WCAG 1.4.1).</li>
  <li>Use direct labels where possible.</li>
  <li>Use different marker shapes or stroke styles for data series.</li>
  <li>Avoid relying solely on red and green distinctions.</li>
  <li>Charts must remain understandable in greyscale.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Pattern fills for colour-blind accessibility</h4>
<p>Use pattern fills as a secondary differentiator for stacked, pie and doughnut charts when adjacent colours are close in tone.</p>

<h5>Requirements</h5>
<ul>
  <li>Pattern strokes and other non-text graphics must meet at least 3 to 1 contrast against adjacent colours and background (WCAG 1.4.11).</li>
  <li>Chart text, labels and legends must still meet 4.5 to 1 contrast (WCAG 1.4.3).</li>
  <li>Do not rely on colour alone. Use colour plus pattern, labels or legends.</li>
</ul>

<h5>Pattern selection and scale</h5>
<ul>
  <li>Use simple patterns that are easy to distinguish, such as diagonal, crosshatch, grid and dots.</li>
  <li>Avoid overly dense or tiny patterns that merge at small sizes.</li>
  <li>Avoid oversized patterns that dominate the chart and distract from data.</li>
  <li>A pattern is too small if the smallest expected data mark cannot show at least 2 to 3 repeats of the motif.</li>
  <li>If pattern detail is lost, simplify the pattern or rely on direct labels and a data table instead.</li>
  <li>Use the swatches below as a scale reference for a medium density pattern in digital charts.</li>
</ul>

